<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-199-724  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 199 724.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  April 17 1989 v23 n16 p72(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Security focus should be inward. (information systems)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Alexander, Michael.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A study by the Los Angeles-based National Center for ComputerCrime Data shows that although information systems (IS) managersand security professionals plan to increase their computersecurity budgets, top management may be forcing those responsiblefor computer security to misdirect their dollars.andP;  The study showsthat expenditures for computer security as a percentage of theoverall computer budget have risen 66 percent since 1987, from 1.4percent in 1986 to 2.3 percent in 1988.andP;  Respondents to the surveystate that they plan to use technologies such as smart cards,audit analysis aids and secure networks.andP;  Foremost Life InsuranceCo system security administrator Ken Shaurette says, however, thatIS managers must be sold a multifaceted security plan that offersseveral strategies, rather than one stressing some methods overothers.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     SecurityStudyInformation SystemsManagementComputersComputer Crime.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>